# Code hygiene rules

## Resource cleanup

- Any `chromium.launch()` / `new Builder().build()` / `createReadStream` / `createWriteStream` / `setInterval` / `setTimeout` / `addEventListener` / `.on(...)` must have a matching release in the same lifetime scope.
- Prefer `try { ... } finally { await browser.close(); await driver.quit(); }` over ad-hoc teardown.
- No `console.log` in library code — use `logger.ts`. `console.*` is allowed in CLI entry (`cli.ts`) and tests.
- Install `SIGINT` / `SIGTERM` handlers in long-running CLI paths so `Ctrl+C` runs the same cleanup as `finally`.

## Comment density

- **Every exported function, exported class, and public method**: 1–3 line doc comment on *purpose + non-obvious intent* (JSDoc/TSDoc `/** … */`, Javadoc, or Python docstring). Include params/returns only when not obvious from types.
- **Private helpers**: comment only when intent is non-obvious (edge case, workaround, perf trade-off, protocol quirk). Self-describing code needs no comment.
- **Forbidden — narration comments** that restate the code: `// increment counter`, `// return result`, `// import the module`, `// loop over items`, `// check if null`.
- **Forbidden — commented-out code**: delete it. If truly needed, move behind a feature flag plus `TODO(owner): <issue-link>`.
- **Allowed — inline caveats**: `// TODO(owner): …`, `// FIXME: …`, `// NOTE: …` — keep short, keep rare.
- **Rule of thumb**: if the comment restates the code, delete it; if it explains *why*, keep it.

## Types & errors (TS)

- No `any` without a one-line justification comment. Prefer `unknown` + narrowing.
- Never throw bare `Error` from driver step execution — wrap in `RunError(stepIndex, step, cause)`.
